I have started collaboration with Peter Brett Associates with respect to a potential karst database for central China</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>There is significant uncertainty regarding risks posed by channelised debris in the Bailong Corridor. VNIR techniques demonstrate considerable potential for reducing such uncertainties and improving knowledge of debris movement, debris origin and landscape evolution.
The nature and triggers for the Zhouqu debris flow disaster were identified, described and published.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>A great deal more work is required to improve models of how to better understand debris production and movement in mountainous regions. This work demonstrated that field investigation is necessary and that suitable remote sensing techniques can yield appropriate information.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>482E3689-5A78-4503-9A48-8EEA9363CF4F</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Construction,Environment,Transport</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/96C9CACD-304F-49EC-8AA9-512295855484"><gtr:id>96C9CACD-304F-49EC-8AA9-512295855484</gtr:id><gtr:title>Geomorphic controls and debris flows - the 2010 Zhouqu disaster, China</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Proceedings of the 11th International Symposium on Landslides</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/3b8b819a72c072f8b8e57be0cc61abb1"><gtr:id>3b8b819a72c072f8b8e57be0cc61abb1</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Dijkstra T</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">NE/I016260/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EE4457DB-92A3-44EA-8D5F-77013CC107E0</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>25</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Climate &amp; Climate Change</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>6E910789-6B8D-4B73-B5B0-F3156942B558</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>55</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Geosciences</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gt